1️⃣ What is allow_any_instance_of?

It stubs a method on every instance of a class.

Example:

allow_any_instance_of(PaymentGateway)
  .to receive(:charge)
  .and_return("Success")

Now:

PaymentGateway.new.charge(100)
PaymentGateway.new.charge(200)
PaymentGateway.new.charge(500)

All of them return "Success".

It affects ALL instances.

🚨 Why It’s Dangerous
❌ 1. It Breaks Test Isolation

You are not controlling a specific object.

You are modifying the behavior of the entire class globally in that test.

This can:

Hide bugs

Affect other expectations

Make debugging harder

❌ 2. It Makes Tests Less Explicit

Look at this:

allow_any_instance_of(User).to receive(:admin?).and_return(true)

Which user?

The one created in the test?

The one created inside the service?

Some other instance?

It’s unclear.

Good tests should be explicit.

❌ 3. It Hides Design Problems

If you need allow_any_instance_of, it often means:

👉 Your object is being created inside the method
👉 You can’t inject dependencies

Example:

class PaymentProcessor
  def call(amount)
    gateway = PaymentGateway.new
    gateway.charge(amount)
  end
end

Now in test, you feel forced to do:

allow_any_instance_of(PaymentGateway)
  .to receive(:charge)

But better design is:

class PaymentProcessor
  def initialize(gateway = PaymentGateway.new)
    @gateway = gateway
  end

  def call(amount)
    @gateway.charge(amount)
  end
end

Now test becomes clean:

gateway = instance_double(PaymentGateway)
allow(gateway).to receive(:charge).and_return("Success")

processor = PaymentProcessor.new(gateway)
processor.call(100)

Much cleaner. Much safer.

❌ 4. Harder to Refactor Safely

If someone changes:

PaymentGateway.new

to:

OtherGateway.new

Your test may silently pass or behave strangely.

Because allow_any_instance_of is broad and implicit.

❌ 5. Considered Code Smell

Even RSpec team discourages it.

Why?

Because it:

Couples test too tightly to implementation

Encourages poor object design

Reduces clarity

🧠 Clean Mental Model

allow_any_instance_of = “I don’t care which instance, just fake them all.”

Good testing = “I know exactly which object I am faking.”

🎯 Interview-Ready Answer

If interviewer asks:

Why is allow_any_instance_of dangerous?

You say:

It globally stubs methods on all instances of a class, which reduces test clarity and isolation. It often indicates poor object design because dependencies are not injected properly. Instead, we should inject dependencies and use instance_double for safer, more explicit tests.

That answer shows senior-level thinking.

🔥 Quick Rule

If you feel the need to use allow_any_instance_of…

Ask yourself:

Can I inject this dependency instead?

If yes → do that.

